  <span id="freeText3391076826799459590" style="display:none">Forgive me for this: there are few books I find myself loving with a passion these days, and this may just be one of them. To think it sat on my shelf for years before I picked it up. <i>The Passion</i> is Angela Carter meets Beryl Bainbridge, but it lacks the bawdy humor present in these ladies' books. It doesn't lack humor, but it treats its subject--love--with great seriousness. Is love worthy of such seriousness? I guess I tend to take a <i>plenty of fish in the sea</i> view, but makes for a nice story, anyway. Like <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/276795.The_Viceroy_of_Ouidah" title="The Viceroy of Ouidah by Bruce Chatwin" rel="nofollow noopener">The Viceroy of Ouidah</a> or <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11728.The_Blue_Flower" title="The Blue Flower by Penelope Fitzgerald" rel="nofollow noopener">The Blue Flower</a>, it is one of the rarities that is concise historical fiction. The way the story alternates between its narrators, Henri and Villanelle, reminds me of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25622780.Wide_Sargasso_Sea" title="Wide Sargasso Sea by Jean Rhys" rel="nofollow noopener">Wide Sargasso Sea</a>--another favorite--and there is even a touch of madness thrown in. It checks all the boxes--as I needed any more reason to love literary Venice--including a PRIDE month read. 🏳️‍🌈 </span>
