  <span id="freeText8388042894077945839" style="display:none">This might be a simple case of bad timing: sometimes, you will cross paths with a book and quite simply not be in the mood for it. After hearing so many praises for Jeanette Winterson’s work, I was very curious, and after reading a big fat book set in the Napoleonic era, I figured an itty-bitty one in the same setting could be a nice change of pace.<br /><br />The story of Henri and Villanelle is written in lovely, poetic prose, but somehow, it left me wanting. Wanting what exactly, I couldn’t tell you. What I do know is that I flipped the last page of “The Passion” feeling like I had been tricked. There was something that struck me as disingenuous and pretentious about the book: I think I was expecting something really deep and moving from this book, and what I got was a paddling pool of unfocused and immature feelings.<br /><br />This fell disappointingly flat for me. Bummer.</span>
