  <span id="freeText12462615263817850515" style="display:none"><i>Passion will not be commanded.....It commands us and very rarely in the way we would choose.</i><br /><br />Henri joins Bonaparte’s new ‘Army of England’, the purpose of which is a cross Channel invasion to bring England into the Empire. The French people are passionate about Napoleon. At this time, they are prepared to follow him anywhere and do. The rest of Europe hates him and in time so will Henri. Bonaparte’s passions are Josephine and chicken which he allegedly eats every day. Henri is chosen to serve him because he is small and Bonaparte refuses to be served by anyone taller than him (which reduces the pool somewhat!).<br /><br />Villanelle is a boatman’s daughter living in Venice and working in a casino. She falls passionately in love with an older woman. Her path and Henri’s meet in the most unexpected way and when they do, the book becomes much more interesting and magical.<br /><br />I enjoyed this as much for the historical setting as for the sometimes beautiful writing. The theme of passion is explored in many different ways so there is a lot to think about. I even enjoyed the fantastical which is unusual for me and there is an underlying humour which often made me smile: <br /><br />Henri is pondering mad King George III of England - <i>Who can fathom the English and their horseradish?<br /><br />The man who walks on water has asked me to include a pond in my garden so that he can practise. He’s an Englishman. What do you expect?</i><br /><br />4 stars because it took me quite a while before suddenly something clicked and I understood where we were going.</span>
