  <span id="freeText12883465647892873677" style="display:none">I read this book lying in the grass and the sand and felt every moment of it, Winterson has a tumultuous way with words - I have loved her writing for a very long time. Blunt, unaplogetically smart and writhing with a desire to articulate - this slim, unusual and reckoning book is astonishing. <br /><br />Reading this novel made me want to lie in pools of red hair left by a girl on a balcony in Venice, it made me want to drink wine and brush my hands against the body of someone I love. It is full of a passion which seethes and delights - this is a novel bursting with colour, flavour, heart-ache and intrigue. Although using figures from history, 'the Passion' works on its own timescale, its characters are like characters from fables or fairytales. It reads like whip-smart folklore. <br /><br />I love what Winterson says about love - that loving someone else allows you to see your own self reflected for the first time, to beg that reflection to be good enough for the object of your desire. She says that between love and fear there lies passion. Passion is what this book is all about: a wild, fabled emotion that fuells everything. <br /><br />I loved this.</span>
